Introduction

   Software-defined networking (SDN) is an approach to computer networking
   that allows network administrators to manage network services through
   abstraction of higher-level functionality. Wiki :
   [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software-defined_networking]Software-Def
   ined Networking

Network Operating System

     * [http://www.pica8.com/products/picos]PicOS - A SDN OS for white box
       switches Layer-2/3 feature set with support for OpenFlow, OVSDB,
       and other protocols.
     * [https://opennetlinux.org/]Open Network Linux, ONL - A Linux
       distribution for "bare metal" switches, that is, network forwarding
       devices built from commodity components.
     * [http://www.openswitch.net/]OpenSwitch - A linux network operating
       system from Dell EMC.
     * [https://cumulusnetworks.com/]Cumulus Linux - Cumulus Linux is a
       powerful open network operating system that allows you to automate,
       customize and scale using web-scale principles like the world's
       largest data centers.
     * [https://www.ipinfusion.com/]OcNOS - Extensive switching and
       routing protocol support with advanced capabilities such as MPLS
       and SDN
     * [https://snaproute.com/]FlexSwitch - The first open source network
       protocol suite offering complete layer2/layer3 functionality for
       accelerating development and deployment of whitebox networking gear
     * [https://github.com/beluganos/beluganos]beluganos - Beluganos is a
       new network OS designed for white-box switches (OF-DPA), which can
       apply large-scale networks.
     * [https://azure.github.io/SONiC/]SONiC - Software for Open
       Networking in the Cloud SONiC

Install Environment

     * [http://onie.org/]ONIE - ONIE enables a bare metal network switch
       ecosystem where end users have a choice among different network
       operating systems.

Software Switch

     * [http://openvswitch.org/]OpenvSwtich - Open vSwitch is a production
       quality, multilayer virtual switch.
     * [https://github.com/floodlight/indigo]Indigo - Indigo is an open
       source project aimed at enabling support for OpenFlow on physical
       and hypervisor switches.
     * [https://github.com/CPqD/ofsoftswitch13]CPqD- An OpenFlow 1.3
       compatible user-space software switch implementation
     * [https://lagopus.github.io/]Lagopus - A high-performance software
       OpenFlow 1.3 switch.
     * [https://github.com/FlowForwarding/LINC-Switch]LINC-Switch - A pure
       OpenFlow software switch written in Erlang
     * [https://github.com/SnabbCo/snabbswitch]snabbswitch - An open
       source virtualized Ethernet networking stack.
     * [https://github.com/zerotier/ZeroTierOne]ZeroTier - ZeroTier is a
       software-based managed Ethernet switch for planet Earth.
     * [http://pisces.cs.princeton.edu/]PISCES - A Programmable,
       Protocol-Independent Software Switch.
     * [https://github.com/NetSys/bess]BESS - Berkeley Extensible Software
       Switch, BESS is a modular framework for software switches.
     * [https://fd.io/]FD.IO - Relentlessly focused on data IO speed and
       efficiency for more flexible and scalable networks and storage

Network Virtualization

     * [https://github.com/opennetworkinglab/flowvisor]FlowVisor - An
       OpenFlow controller that acts as a hypervisor/proxy between a
       switch and multiple controllers. Can slice multiple switches in
       parallel, effectively slicing a network.
     * [https://github.com/opennetworkinglab/OpenVirteX]OpenVirtex - A
       network hypervisor that can create multiple virtual and
       programmable networks on top of a single physical infrastructure.

Protocol

     * [https://www.opennetworking.org/sdn-resources/openflow]OpenFlow - A
       communications protocol that gives access to the forwarding plane
       of a network switch or router over the network.
     * [https://www.opennetworking.org/technical-communities/areas/specifi
       cation/1928-of-config]OF-Config - OpenFlow Management and
       Configuration Protocol
     * [https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7047]OVSDB - A communication
       protocol which used to manage the OpenvSwitch database.
     * [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NETCONF]NETCONF
     * [http://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/solutions/collateral/data-center-virt
       ualization/application-centric-infrastructure/white-paper-c11-73130
       2.html]OpFlex
     * [https://www.juniper.net/documentation/en_US/junos/topics/concept/m
       pls-pcep-overview.html]Path Computation Element Protocol, PCEP
     * [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XMPP]Extensible Messaging and
       Presence Protocol, XMPP

Controller

     * [https://github.com/noxrepo/nox]NOX - An open source development
       platform for C++-based software-defined networking (SDN) control
       applications.
     * [https://github.com/noxrepo/pox]POX - An open source development
       platform for Python-based software-defined networking (SDN) control
       applications.
     * [https://github.com/gaberger/NodeFLow]NodeFlow - An OpenFlow
       Controller Node Style.
     * [http://onosproject.org/]ONOS - Open Network Operating System.
     * [https://www.opendaylight.org/]OpenDaylight - OpenDaylight Platform
     * [https://osrg.github.io/ryu]Ryu - A component-based software
       defined networking framework.
     * [https://github.com/floodlight/floodlight]Floodlight - A java-based
       OpenFlow controller.
     * [https://github.com/BRCDcomm/BVC/]Vyatta - The first commercial
       Controller built directly from OpenDaylight.
     * [http://www.opencontrail.org/]OpenContrail - A SDN project that
       utilizes SDN & NFV and provides all the necessary components for
       network virtualization.
     * [http://openiris.etri.re.kr/]IRIS - A Resursive SDN Openflow
       Controller created by SDN Research Section, ETRI.
     * [http://www.openmul.org/openmul-controller.html]Open MUL - A
       lightweight SDN/Openflow controller written almost entirely in C
       from scratch.
     * [https://github.com/globalnoc/oess]OESS - The Open Exchange
       Software Suite to configure and control OpenFlow Enabled switches.
     * [https://github.com/kandoo/beehive-netctrl]Beehive Network
       Controller - A distributed SDN controller built on top of Beehive.
       It supports OpenFlow but can be easily extended for other
       southbound protocols.
     * [https://github.com/ravel-net/ravel]Ravel - A software-defined
       networking (SDN) controller that uses a standard SQL database to
       represent the network.
     * [https://trema.github.io/trema/]Trema - A full-stack, easy-to-use
       framework for developing OpenFlow controllers in Ruby and C.
     * [https://www.opensecuritycontroller.org/]Open Security Controller -
       Software-defined security orchestration solution that automates
       deployment of virtualized network security functions, like
       next-generation firewall, intrusion prevention systems and
       application data controllers
     * [https://github.com/netrack/openflow]Netrack - An OpenFlow
       controller framework in Go.

Simulator/Emulator

     * [http://mininet.org/]Mininet - An Instant Virtual Network on your
       Laptop (or other PC)
     * [http://github.com/dlinknctu/opennet]OpenNet - A simulator for
       software-defined wireless local area network
     * [http://www.estinet.com/products.php?lv1=13&sn=13]EstiNet - A
       world-renowned software tool for network planning
     * [https://www.nsnam.org/]ns-3 - A discrete-event network simulator
       that supports OpenFlow environment.
     * [https://github.com/containernet/containernet]Containernet -
       Mininet fork that allows to use Docker containers as hosts in
       emulated networks
     * [https://github.com/John-Lin/tinynet]Tinynet - A lightweight
       instant virtual network for rapid prototyping SDN
     * [http://maxinet.github.io/]MaxiNet - MaxiNet extends the famous
       Mininet emulation environment to span the emulation across several
       physical machines. This allows to emulate very large
       software-defined networks.

Language

     * [http://p4.org/]P4 - A declarative language for expressing how
       packets are processed by the pipeline of a network forwarding
       element such as a switch, NIC, router or network function
       appliance.
     * [https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=2491190]POF - Protocol
       Oblivious Forwarding
     * [https://github.com/frenetic-lang/frenetic]Frenetic - The Frenetic
       Programming Language and Runtime System
     * [http://www.frenetic-lang.org/pyretic/]Pyretic - Pyretic is one
       member of the Frenetic family of SDN programming languages.
     * [https://wiki.onosproject.org/display/ONOS/NEMO+Language]NEMO - A
       domain specific language (DSL) based on abstraction of network
       models and conclusion of operation patterns.

Library

     * [https://github.com/floodlight/loxigen]loxigen - LoxiGen is a tool
       that generates OpenFlow protocol libraries for a number of
       languages.
     * [https://github.com/rlenglet/openfaucet]openfaucet - openfaucet is
       a pure Python implementation of the OpenFlow 1.0.0 protocol, based
       on Twisted.
     * [https://github.com/TrafficLab/oflib-node]oflib-node - Oflib-node
       is an OpenFlow protocol library for Node. It converts between
       OpenFlow wire protocol messages and Javascript objects.
     * [https://bitbucket.org/openflowj/openflowj]OpenFlowJ - A Java
       implementation of low-level OpenFlow packet
       marshalling/unmarshalling and IO operations.
     * [https://github.com/AndreasVoellmy/openflow]nettle - A Haskell
       library for working with the OpenFlow protocol.
     * [https://github.com/frenetic-lang/ocaml-openflow]OCaml OpenFlow - A
       serialization and protocol library for OpenFlow.
     * [http://www.secdev.org/projects/scapy/]Scapy - Scapy is a powerful
       interactive packet manipulation program.

Test

     * [https://github.com/floodlight/oftest]oftest - OpenFlow Testing
       Framework
     * [https://ucb-sts.github.com/sts/]STS - SDN Troubleshooting System,
       simulates network devices, allowing programmatically test cases
       generation.
     * [https://code.google.com/archive/p/nice-of/]nice-of - A tool to
       test OpenFlow controller application for the NOX controller
       platform.
     * [http://www.opensdncore.org/]OpenSDNCore - Virtualisation Testbed
       for NFV/SDN Environment.
     * [https://github.com/mininet/oflops/tree/master/cbench]Cbenech -
       Benchmarking tool for controllers

NFV

     * [https://www.opnfv.org/]OPNFV - Accelerating NFV's evolution
       through an integrated, open platform.

Overlay Network

     * [https://docs.ustack.com/unp/src/architecture/vxlan.html]VXLAN -
       Virtual Extensible LAN
     * [https://tools.ietf.org/html/draft-sridharan-virtualization-nvgre-0
       0]NVGRE -
       NVGRE-Network-Virtualization-using-Generic-Routing-Encapsulation

Router

     * [http://freerouter.nop.hu/]FreeRouter - Java-based vRouter
     * [http://bird.network.cz/]Bird
     * [http://www.quagga.net/]Quagga
     * [https://frrouting.org/]FRRouting - An IP routing protocol suite
       for Linux and Unix platforms which includes protocol daemons for
       BGP4, BGP4+, OSPFv2, OSPFv3, RIPv1, RIPv2, RIPng, PIM-SM/MSDP and
       LDP as well as very early support for IS-IS, EIGRP and NHRP.
     * [https://projects.bytemark.co.uk/projects/bgpfeeder]BGPFeeder
     * [https://github.com/jesnault/bgp4r]bgp4r
     * [https://github.com/osrg/gobgp]gobgp
     * [https://github.com/smartbgp/yabgp]yabgp

Misc

     * [http://opencord.org/]Central Office Re-architected as a
       Datacenter, CORD - Reference Implementation of a Service Delivery
       Platform that Provides Cloud Economies and Agility.
     * [https://www.open-o.org/]OPEN-Orchestrator Project, Open-O
     * [https://osm.etsi.org/welcome/]Open Source MANO Community, OSM
     * [http://att.com/ecomp]Enhanced Controller Orchestration Management
       Policy, ECOMP - Operations management framework.
     * [https://www.onap.org/]Open Network Automation Platform, ONAP -
       Alignment of the two projects creates a harmonized and
       comprehensive framework for real-time, policy-driven software
       automation of virtual network functions that will enable software,
       network, IT and cloud providers and developers to rapidly create
       new services.
     * [http://mininet.spear.narmox.com/]Mininet Spear Narmox - A online
       web service provides a visualization of Mininet Topology

High Performance Network

     * [http://dpdk.org/]DPDK - DPDK is a set of libraries and drivers for
       fast packet processing. It is designed to run on any processors.
       The first supported CPU was Intel x86 and it is now extended to IBM
       POWER and ARM.
     * [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remote_direct_memory_access]RDMA -
       Remote direct memory access (RDMA) is a direct memory access from
       the memory of one computer into that of another without involving
       either one's operating system. This permits high-throughput,
       low-latency networking
     * [https://www.iovisor.org/technology/xdp]XDP - XDP or eXpress Data
       Path provides a high performance, programmable network data path in
       the Linux kernel as part of the IO Visor Project.
     * [http://www.mellanox.com/blog/2016/12/three-ways-asap2-beats-dpdk-f
       or-cloud-and-nfv/]ASAP2 - The ASAP2 accelerator is built on top of
       eSwitch NIC hardware, and allows either the entire virtual switch,
       or significant portions of virtual switch or distributed virtual
       router (DVR) operations to be offloaded to the Mellanox NIC

Userspace Network Stack

     * [https://github.com/eunyoung14/mtcp]mTCP - mTCP is a highly
       scalable user-level TCP stack for multicore systems. mTCP source
       code is distributed under the Modified BSD License. For more
       detail, please refer to the LICENSE. The license term of io_engine
       driver and ported applications may differ from the mTCP's.
     * [https://github.com/libos-nuse/net-next-nuse]net-next-nuse -
       Network Stack in Userspace (NUSE) NUSE allows us to use Linux
       network stack as a library which any applications can directory use
       by linking the library. Each application has its own network stack
       so, it provides an instant virtualized environment apart from a
       host operating system.
     * [https://github.com/rumpkernel/drv-netif-dpdk]drv-netif-dpdk -
       drv-netif-dpdk is a DPDK network interface for rump kernels. The
       combined result is a userspace TCP/IP stack doing packet I/O via
       DPDK.
     * [https://github.com/F-Stack/f-stack]f-stack - F-Stack is an user
       space network development kit with high performance based on DPDK,
       FreeBSD TCP/IP stack and coroutine API.
     * [https://github.com/intel-go/yanff]yanff - YANFF is a set of
       libraries for creating and deploying cloud-native Network Functions
       (NFs). It simplifies the creation of network functions without
       sacrificing performance.

Analytics

     * [http://pnda.io/]PNDA - The scalable, open source big data
       analytics platform for networks and services.
     * [http://www.snas.io/]SNAS - Streaming Network Analytics System
       (project SNAS) is a framework to collect, track and access tens of
       millions of routing objects (routers, peers, prefixes) in real
       time.
     * [http://spot.incubator.apache.org/]Apache Spot - Community-driven
       cybersecurity project, built from the ground up, to bring advanced
       analytics to all IT Telemetry data on an open, scalable platform

